\begin{abstract}
We address image classification on the Caltech-101 dataset using both transfer learning with deep networks and classical pipelines based on hand-crafted features. We compare three pretrained architectures (ResNet-18, EfficientNet-B0, and Vision Transformer (ViT-B/16)) with frozen backbones and a trainable head, alongside HOG features with SVM and logistic regression. We ablate input resolution, data augmentation, and optimizer choice, and report accuracy, top-5 accuracy, and per-class precision, recall, and F1. ViT-B/16 achieves the best test accuracy (95.93\%); ResNet-18 and EfficientNet-B0 reach 92.55\% and 94.62\% at 224$\times$224; classical HOG+LR reaches 66.05\% at 64$\times$64.
\end{abstract}

%==============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
%==============================================================================
We consider image classification on Caltech-101~\cite{caltech101} with 101 object categories. Understanding how design choices (resolution, augmentation, optimizer) and feature type (hand-crafted vs.\ learned) affect performance is useful for low-resource or interpretability-sensitive settings. We use (i) transfer learning from ImageNet-pretrained~\cite{imagenet} deep networks (ResNet-18~\cite{resnet}, EfficientNet-B0~\cite{efficientnet}, ViT-B/16~\cite{vit}) with only the classification head trained, and (ii) classical pipelines using HOG features~\cite{hog} with SVM and logistic regression. The main comparisons are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:intro}. We describe data processing and model architectures in Section~\ref{sec:methods}, experimental setup and results in Section~\ref{sec:experiments} and Section~\ref{sec:results}, and discuss these four dimensions in Section~\ref{sec:discussion}; Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes.

