%==============================================================================
\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}
%==============================================================================
This section covers data processing (splits, preprocessing, augmentation) and the architectures of all models used.

%----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Data Processing}
\label{sec:data}
%----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\paragraph{Dataset and splits.}
We use the Caltech-101 dataset~\cite{caltech101}: 101 object categories, 8,677 images after excluding the \texttt{BACKGROUND\_Google} clutter class. Class sizes are imbalanced (roughly 31--800 images per category). With a fixed random seed we perform a stratified 70/15/15 split into train (6,073), validation (1,302), and test (1,302) sets; the same split is used for all models and ablations.

\paragraph{Preprocessing for deep learning.}
Images are loaded in RGB and resized to a target resolution (64, 128, or 224 pixels per side, depending on the experiment). For training we apply random resized crop (scale 0.8--1.0), random horizontal flip, and color jitter (brightness, contrast, saturation), then convert to tensor and normalize with ImageNet~\cite{imagenet} mean and standard deviation. For validation and test we only resize to the same resolution, then normalize. One ablation disables augmentation (resize and normalize only).

\paragraph{Preprocessing for classical baselines.}
For HOG-based pipelines we load images, convert to grayscale, and resize to the target size (64 or 128). We then compute Histogram of Oriented Gradients (HOG)~\cite{hog} features: each image is described by local gradient orientation histograms over overlapping cells and blocks (orientations=9, pixels per cell 8$\times$8, cells per block 2$\times$2, L2-Hys block normalization). HOG summarizes edge and contour structure in a fixed-length vector and does not capture texture or high-level semantics. The resulting feature vectors are standardized with \texttt{StandardScaler} (fit on train, transform on train/val/test). We report test accuracy, top-5 accuracy, and F1 (macro and weighted) for all HOG baselines in the results.

%----------------------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Model Architectures}
\label{sec:models}
%----------------------------------------------------------------------------

\paragraph{ResNet-18.}
ResNet-18~\cite{resnet} is a 18-layer residual network: initial conv layer, four stages of residual blocks (2+2+2+2 blocks) with 64, 128, 256, 512 channels, global average pooling, and a fully connected layer. We load ImageNet-pretrained weights from torchvision, freeze all parameters except the final layer, and replace the final layer with a linear layer mapping to 101 classes. Input size can be 64, 128, or 224 (spatially); the backbone adapts to the input size through the global pooling.

\paragraph{EfficientNet-B0.}
EfficientNet-B0~\cite{efficientnet} uses compound scaling (depth, width, resolution) and mobile inverted bottleneck (MBConv) blocks with squeeze-and-excitation. We use the torchvision implementation with ImageNet pretrained weights, freeze the entire backbone, and replace the classifier (a dropout and linear layer) with a new dropout and linear layer for 101 classes. Input resolution is varied in ablations (64, 128, 224).

\paragraph{Vision Transformer (ViT-B/16).}
ViT-B/16~\cite{vit} splits the image into 16$\times$16 patches, embeds them linearly, adds a learnable [CLS] token and positional embeddings, and processes the sequence with a Transformer encoder (12 layers, hidden size 768, 12 heads). The classification head is a linear layer on the [CLS] token. We use the torchvision ViT-B/16 with ImageNet weights; input is fixed at 224$\times$224. We do not ablate image size for ViT: the pretrained positional embeddings are defined for a fixed 14$\times$14 patch grid (224/16), so 64$\times$64 or 128$\times$128 would require interpolating them to a different grid size (e.g., 4$\times$4 or 8$\times$8), and at 64$\times$64 the model would see only 16 patches versus 196 at 224, which would poorly match the pretrained distribution. We therefore keep ViT at its native 224$\times$224 for a fair transfer-learning comparison. We freeze all parameters except the final head.

\paragraph{HOG + SVM.}
We extract a fixed-length HOG descriptor per image (as in Section~\ref{sec:data}). A linear SVM (\texttt{LinearSVC})~\cite{svm} is trained on the standardized features in a one-vs-rest scheme. For probability estimates and top-$k$ accuracy we wrap the SVM with \texttt{CalibratedClassifierCV} (sigmoid method, 2-fold cross-validation).

\paragraph{HOG + Logistic Regression.}
Using the same HOG features and scaling, we train a multinomial logistic regression (L2 regularization, LBFGS solver) for 101-way classification. The single multinomial model directly learns decision boundaries among all 101 classes. No calibration step is needed for probabilities.

