\subsection{Ablation Design}
We conduct comparisons along four dimensions:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Image size}: compare 64$\times$64 vs.\ 128$\times$128 (and 224$\times$224 for ResNet and EfficientNet where applicable). ViT-B/16 is not ablated over resolution because its pretrained positional embeddings assume a 224$\times$224 input (see Section~\ref{sec:models}).
  \item \textbf{Data augmentation}: train with vs.\ without augmentation (CNNs only).
  \item \textbf{Feature extractor choice}: HOG (hand-crafted) vs.\ CNN features (ResNet-18, EfficientNet-B0, ViT-B/16 transfer learning).
  \item \textbf{Optimizer}: SGD vs.\ Adam for CNN; we also include AdamW for completeness.
\end{itemize}
All CNN ablations (image size, augmentation, optimizer) use the same evaluation protocol; classical HOG+SVM and HOG+LR runs provide the feature-extractor comparison.

\subsection{Evaluation}
We report overall accuracy and top-5 accuracy on the test set, and per-class precision, recall, and F1 with macro and weighted averages. Confusion matrices are produced for all baselines (including HOG+SVM and HOG+LR at 64 and 128); per-class accuracy and F1 bar plots are produced for the CNN baselines only (see Section~\ref{sec:results}). Reproducibility is ensured by a fixed random seed and, for PyTorch, deterministic worker initialization when using multiple DataLoader workers. All results are from a single train/val/test split; we report point estimates without confidence intervals.

