\paragraph{Summary: confusion matrices and per-class accuracy.}
The confusion matrices (Figures~\ref{fig:cm-resnet}--\ref{fig:cm-hog-lr128}) show a clear gradient from CNN baselines to the classical baselines: ResNet-18, EfficientNet-B0, and ViT-B/16 exhibit strong diagonal dominance with limited off-diagonal mass, whereas HOG+SVM and HOG+LR have noisier matrices with more diffuse confusions; HOG+LR yields stronger diagonal dominance than HOG+SVM at both resolutions. Within the CNNs, ViT at 224$\times$224 concentrates errors in fewer classes and yields the cleanest diagonal. The per-class accuracy plots (Figures~\ref{fig:perclass-resnet}--\ref{fig:perclass-vit}) align with this: all three CNN baselines perform well on many categories, with dips typically in rare or visually ambiguous classes (e.g., fine-grained animals or objects with high intra-class variation). ViT raises the floor across classes compared with ResNet-18 and EfficientNet-B0 at 128$\times$128. Taken together, the confusion matrices and per-class accuracy indicate that (i) learned CNN features yield more separable class representations than HOG, (ii) higher resolution (224) improves both overall accuracy and per-class consistency, and (iii) the remaining errors are concentrated in a small set of difficult categories rather than spread uniformly.


%==============================================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
%==============================================================================
\subsection{Observations and Ablation Studies}
\paragraph{Image size: 64$\times$64 vs.\ 128$\times$128 (and 224).}
For ResNet-18 and EfficientNet-B0, test accuracy drops sharply at 64$\times$64 (around 60--66\% and 54--58\% depending on augment/optimizer) compared with 128 (84--86\% and 79--85\%) and 224 (91--92.5\% and 88--94.6\%). Larger resolution consistently helps; ViT-B/16 (fixed at 224) reaches the highest accuracy (95.93\% without augmentation, 95.55\% with). The 64 vs.\ 128 comparison clearly favors 128 for both architectures.

\paragraph{Data augmentation: with vs.\ without.}
Training without augmentation yields similar or slightly better test accuracy at 128 for ResNet (85.79\% no aug vs.\ 85.94\% with aug) and EfficientNet (84.64--84.79\% no aug vs.\ 83.95--85.1\% with aug); for ViT at 224, no augmentation slightly outperforms (95.93\% vs.\ 95.55\%). Overall, the effect of augmentation is modest in this setting, suggesting limited overfitting when augmentation is disabled.

\paragraph{Feature extractor choice: HOG vs.\ CNN.}
The classical baselines HOG+SVM and HOG+LR were evaluated at 64$\times$64 and 128$\times$128. HOG+SVM reaches 54.61\% test (64) and 49.92\% (128); HOG+LR reaches 66.05\% (64) and 65.90\% (128) test accuracy, with top-5 about 82\% in both cases. Thus HOG+LR substantially outperforms HOG+SVM on this dataset. All CNN baselines (ResNet-18, EfficientNet-B0, ViT-B/16) substantially outperform both classical methods. Learned CNN features clearly outperform hand-crafted HOG on Caltech-101 under our setup.

\paragraph{Optimizer: SGD vs.\ Adam (and AdamW) for CNN.}
SGD underperforms Adam and AdamW: e.g., ResNet-18 at 128 (83.33\% SGD vs.\ 85.94\% Adam/AdamW); EfficientNet-B0 at 128 (80.11\% SGD vs.\ 85.1\% AdamW). At 224, ResNet-18 reaches 92.55\% (Adam) vs.\ 91.4\% (SGD); EfficientNet-B0 reaches 94.62\% (Adam) vs.\ 89.55\% (SGD). Adam and AdamW are close; Adam is the default and performs well across families.
\subsection{Analysis of Performance Drivers}
The results indicate that the dominant performance gain comes from moving from hand-crafted HOG features to learned CNN/ViT representations. HOG+LR saturates around 66\% accuracy at 64$\times$64, whereas pretrained backbones with a linear head achieve above 90\%, showing that learned hierarchical features provide much richer class separation than fixed gradient histograms.

\subsection{The Role of Input Resolution and Feature Alignment}
Input resolution emerged as a critical bottleneck for convolutional architectures. The sharp decline in accuracy at 64$\times$64 (e.g., 60.60\% for ResNet-18) compared to 224$\times$224 (92.55\%) indicates that aggressive downsampling discards the fine-grained discriminative textures (such as the specific contours of animal species) that ImageNet-pretrained filters are tuned to detect. Furthermore, because models like ResNet and EfficientNet were originally optimized for 224-pixel inputs, feeding them smaller images likely introduces a distribution shift that hinders the performance of the pre-extracted features. ViT-B/16's superior performance (95.93\%) further underscores this, as its patch-based attention mechanism effectively captures global context that global average pooling in CNNs might compress too aggressively at lower resolutions.

\subsection{Optimization and Regularization Nuances}
Contrary to some common assumptions in deep learning, data augmentation yielded only marginal gains in this head-only transfer learning setup. In several instances, such as with ViT-B/16, training without augmentation slightly outperformed the augmented runs. This phenomenon can be attributed to the fact that we are only training a linear classification head; since the backbone remains frozen, the risk of overfitting is inherently limited, and the noise introduced by augmentation may occasionally interfere with the stable features already learned during pretraining. 

Regarding optimization, the consistent advantage of Adam/AdamW over SGD (e.g., a 5\% gap for EfficientNet-B0 at 224) suggests that adaptive learning rates are better suited for fine-tuning a single layer. SGD's reliance on a global learning rate appears less efficient at navigating the loss surface of the classification head when the underlying feature extractor is not co-adapting.

\subsection{Limitations and Future Trajectories}
While the results are robust, several constraints merit acknowledgment. The use of a single stratified split provides point estimates but does not account for the variance inherent in class-imbalanced datasets like Caltech-101. Additionally, the study is limited to linear probing (frozen backbones). A natural extension would be a comparative study of full fine-tuning versus head-only training to determine if the 4\% error rate remaining in ViT can be closed by adapting the lower-level filters to Caltech's specific domain.

%==============================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
%==============================================================================
This study evaluated the interplay between architectural design, input resolution, and optimization strategies for image classification. Our findings confirm that representation quality, driven by pretrained transformers and deep residual networks, dominates performance. Code, experiment logs, figures, and the report source are available at \url{https://github.com/chenxige0509/Caltech101-Mini-Project}.

